<paragraph blockId="33.[151,1436,1614,2036]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">
<emphasis box="[199,359,1614,1639]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Apical system</emphasis>
—Situated close to centre, 50–56% TL from anterior margin; with four circular gonopores, single hydropore, sometimes distorted to resemble groove with two or three hydropores (
<figureCitation box="[1148,1232,1650,1675]" captionStart="FIGURE 26" captionStartId="34.[151,250,1873,1895]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,406,1851]" captionTargetId="figure@34.[151,1436,406,1851]" captionTargetPageId="34" captionText="FIGURE 26. SEM images showing details of apical system of Echinocyamus megapetalus: A, WUSL/EI/195; B, WUSL/EI/ 196; C, WUSL/EI/197." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2617511/files/figure.png" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Fig. 26</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="33.[151,1436,1614,2036]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">
<emphasis box="[199,323,1686,1711]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Ambulacra</emphasis>
—Petaloid region length more than half TL (75–90% TL); petal III with 7–14 pore pairs, anterior paired petals with 5–12 pore pairs, posterior paired petals with 7–13 pore pairs; petals broad, open distally; pore series diverging; interporiferous zones wider than poriferous zones.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="33.[151,1436,1614,2036]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">
<emphasis box="[199,313,1796,1819]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Peristome</emphasis>
—Elongate pentagonal; moderate size, length 20–28% TL, width 16–22% TL, slightly anterior of centre, 38–42% TL from anterior margin, infundibulum deep.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="33.[151,1436,1614,2036]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">
<emphasis box="[199,305,1868,1891]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Periproct</emphasis>
—Small, 9–12% TL; transversely oval; wider than long, width 11–14% TL; inframarginal, 14–23% TL from posterior margin.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="33.[151,1436,1614,2036]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,418,1938,1963]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Geographic range</emphasis>
. Indo-West Pacific, from 
<collectingCountry box="[727,836,1938,1963]" name="Mauritius" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Mauritius</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Clark, H. L." box="[855,987,1938,1963]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" pagination="1 - 78" refId="ref34266" refString="Clark, H. L. (1914) Hawaiian and other Pacific Echini-the Clypeasteridae, Arachnoididae, Laganidae, Fibulariidae, and Scutellidae. Memoirs of the Museum of Comparative Zoology, 46, 1 - 78." type="journal article" year="1914">Clark 1914</bibRefCitation>
) to Coral Sea (
<bibRefCitation author="Miskelly, A." box="[1174,1346,1938,1963]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" refId="ref35198" refString="Miskelly, A. (2002) Sea urchins of Australia and the Indo-Pacific. Capricornica Publications, Lindfield, 179 pp." type="book" year="2002">Miskelly 2002</bibRefCitation>
), South Pacific Islands (
<bibRefCitation author="Clark, A. H." box="[329,459,1974,1999]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" pagination="243 - 263" refId="ref34205" refString="Clark, A. H. (1954) Records of Indo-Pacific echinoderms. Pacific Science, 8, 243 - 263." type="journal article" year="1954">Clark 1954</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Mortensen, T." box="[471,669,1974,1999]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" refId="ref35386" refString="Mortensen, T. (1948 b) A Monograph of the Echinoidea IV. 2. Clypeasteroida. Clypeasteridae, Arachnoidae, Fibulariidae, Laganidae and Scutellidae. C. A. Reitzel, Copenhagen, 471 pp." type="book" year="1948">Mortensen 1948b</bibRefCitation>
) and Hawaiian Islands (
<bibRefCitation author="Mortensen, T." box="[940,1143,1974,1999]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" refId="ref35386" refString="Mortensen, T. (1948 b) A Monograph of the Echinoidea IV. 2. Clypeasteroida. Clypeasteridae, Arachnoidae, Fibulariidae, Laganidae and Scutellidae. C. A. Reitzel, Copenhagen, 471 pp." type="book" year="1948">Mortensen 1948b</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="33.[151,1436,1614,2036]" box="[199,735,2011,2036]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,430,2011,2036]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Bathymetric range.</emphasis>
<quantity box="[437,537,2011,2036]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.75" metricValueMax="7.5" metricValueMin="2.0" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" unit="m" value="47.5" valueMax="75.0" valueMin="20.0">20–75 m</quantity>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Markello, K. M." box="[551,723,2011,2036]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" refId="ref35141" refString="Markello, K. M. (2015) Phylogenetic revision of the micro-echinoid genus, Echinocyamus. San Francisco State University, San Francisco, California, 308 pp." type="book" year="2015">Markello 2015</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="34.[151,1436,151,351]" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,583,151,176]" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">
Observed occurrence in 
<collectingCountry box="[452,577,151,176]" name="Sri Lanka" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">Sri Lanka</collectingCountry>
.
</emphasis>
Only denuded tests were found on the beach of Hiriketiya Bay, southern coast of Sri Lanka (
<figureCitation box="[371,455,185,210]" captionStart="FIGURE 27" captionStartId="35.[151,250,1877,1899]" captionTargetBox="[187,1426,224,1832]" captionTargetId="figure@35.[151,1436,193,1856]" captionTargetPageId="35" captionText="FIGURE 27. Distribution map of Echinocyamus megapetalus, Fibularia ovulum and Fibularia sp. recorded in this study." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2617513/files/figure.png" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">Fig. 27</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="34" pageNumber="35" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="34.[151,1436,151,351]" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,218,243]" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">Remarks.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName box="[322,495,218,243]" class="Echinoidea" family="Fibulariidae" genus="Echinocyamus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Clypeasteroida" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="megapetalus">
<emphasis box="[322,495,218,243]" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">E. megapetalus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is recorded for the first time in 
<collectingCountry box="[852,965,218,243]" name="Sri Lanka" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">Sri Lanka</collectingCountry>
. 
<taxonomicName box="[975,1149,218,243]" class="Echinoidea" family="Fibulariidae" genus="Echinocyamus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Clypeasteroida" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="megapetalus">
<emphasis box="[975,1149,218,243]" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">E. megapetalus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is similar to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Mazzetti" authorityYear="1893" box="[1295,1407,220,243]" class="Echinoidea" family="Fibulariidae" genus="Echinocyamus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Clypeasteroida" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="crispus">
<emphasis box="[1295,1407,220,243]" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">E. crispus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in having a deep infundibulum but 
<taxonomicName box="[534,711,254,279]" class="Echinoidea" family="Fibulariidae" genus="Echinocyamus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Clypeasteroida" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="megapetalus">
<emphasis box="[534,711,254,279]" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">E. megapetalus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is easily distinguished from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Mazzetti" authorityYear="1893" box="[1052,1167,255,278]" class="Echinoidea" family="Fibulariidae" genus="Echinocyamus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Clypeasteroida" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="crispus">
<emphasis box="[1052,1167,255,278]" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">E. crispus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and other Indo-Pacific species by having broad, diverging petals that cover the majority of the aboral surface and by its deep infundibulum. However, studied specimens show great variation in test size and petaloid area length.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
